references: In previous sections, we validate the presence of source bias in recommender systems. Furthermore, with the proliferation of AIGC on the internet, source bias amplifies throughout the feedback loop, thus accelerating the expansion of AIGC. Therefore, it is crucial to propose an effective debiasing method and maintain its effectiveness in dynamically changing feedback loop scenarios. In previous work, some effective methods (Dai et al., 2024c; Xu et al., 2024a) to mitigate source bias have been suggested in document ranking and text-image retrieval tasks. However, these methods can not be directly applied to the dynamic feedback loop scenarios of recommender systems. (Dai et al., 2024c; Xu et al., 2024a) to mitigate source bias have been suggested in document ranking and text-image retrieval tasks. However, these methods can not be directly applied to the dynamic feedback loop scenarios of recommender systems. First, these methods focus on debiasing document representations while overlooking context representations that are intertwined with AIGC and expand with the progression of the feedback loop. This expansion contributes to the amplification of source bias. Second, previous methods are white-box and therefore require knowledge of whether the text comes from HGC or AIGC, which is challenging to achieve in the context of a feedback loop, even with text detection techniques. Third, these methods utilize hinge loss, which may cause the model to gradually favor HGC during the feedback loop process, leading to the development of new biases. Moreover, we employ the debiasing methods from previous studies to train the model in a feedback loop, and the results in Table 4 demonstrate the necessity of new methods in dynamic scenarios.
